# STRATEGICLAND — Image Treatment System

> Images are not **assets**. Images are **artifacts**.
> The audience must feel they have **discovered** an image, not been **shown** one.
> Every image must look like it was photographed for this site, even if it wasn't.

---

## 1. Image Philosophy

- Images live inside the **atmosphere** of the chapter — they are graded into it, not pasted on top.
- Images are **revealed**, never **placed**. There is no such thing as an image that just appears.
- Crop, weight, and composition matter more than the image itself. A weak image well-composed beats a strong image carelessly placed.
- Stock imagery is **forbidden**. Editorial, documentary, and original photography only.

---

## 2. Image Asset Standards

### 2.1 Format priority
1. **AVIF** — primary format (best compression, modern browsers).
2. **WebP** — fallback.
3. **JPG** — ultimate fallback for ancient browsers.

Use Next.js `<Image>` component (App Router) — it handles format negotiation automatically. Verify against `node_modules/next/dist/docs/` for any Next 16 specifics.

### 2.2 Color depth & profile
- Embedded sRGB profile only.
- 8-bit per channel (10-bit AVIF only for hero rare cases).
- Convert all source assets to sRGB before delivery.

### 2.3 Naming
- `images/<chapter>/<scene>-<descriptor>.avif`
- Example: `images/drift/scene02-foglake.avif`
- No spaces, lowercase, kebab-case.

### 2.4 Sizes
- Hero images: max **2400×1600px** (3:2) source. Below 600 KB AVIF.
- Editorial images: max **1800×1200px** source. Below 400 KB AVIF.
- Case study slides: max **2000×1500px**. Below 500 KB AVIF.
- Inline thumbnails: max **800×600px**. Below 120 KB AVIF.

---

## 3. Crop Philosophy

- Crops are **deliberate framing**, not "make it fit". Every crop must respect the image's narrative center.
- Default editorial crop ratios:
  - Hero / cinematic: **2.39:1** (anamorphic) or **2:1**.
  - Editorial portrait: **3:4** (classic editorial vertical).
  - Editorial landscape: **3:2**.
  - Square: **1:1** — used rarely, only as deliberate punctuation.

### Constraints
- Never crop a face below the eyes or above the chin (unless deliberately abstract).
- Never crop hands at the wrist (creates "cut limb" effect).
- Never use circular crops on photographs.
- Always honor the **rule of negative space** — leave breathing room in the direction the subject "looks" or "moves".

---

## 4. Image Reveal Systems

The project ships **3 canonical reveal patterns**. Choose by context, never invent new ones.

### 4.1 Mask Reveal (default for editorial images)
- `clip-path: inset(0 100% 0 0)` → `inset(0 0 0 0)` — reveals from left to right.
- Direction may be reversed for asymmetric pairings (left of column → reveal from right).
- Duration: `DUR.cinematic` (1.2s).
- Ease: `EASE.cinematic`.
- Image inside the mask scales **slightly** during reveal: `scale(1.04)` → `scale(1.0)` for a "settling" feel.

```tsx
<RevealImage src="..." direction="left-to-right" />
```

### 4.2 Blur Reveal (used for hero / atmospheric images)
- `filter: blur(20px)` → `blur(0)` over `DUR.cinematic`.
- Combined with `opacity: 0` → `1`.
- Combined with `scale(1.06)` → `scale(1.0)`.
- Used **at most twice per page** — expensive on GPU.

### 4.3 Edge-Drift Reveal (used for case study slides)
- Image translates from `yPercent: 8` → `0` while opacity 0 → 1.
- Inner image translates inverse `yPercent: -4` → `0` to create parallax-on-entry depth.
- Used during pinned horizontal storytelling.

### Reveal constraints
- Every reveal triggers **once** per scroll direction. No re-reveal on scroll-up.
- All reveals respect `prefers-reduced-motion` (opacity-only fallback).
- No reveal animates `width`, `height`, `top`, `left`. Use `clip-path`, `transform`, `filter`, `opacity` only.

---

## 5. Image Atmosphere Treatment

Every image on the site receives **3 atmospheric layers** automatically (via `<EditorialImage>` wrapper):

1. **Grain overlay** — `mix-blend-mode: overlay`, opacity 0.05–0.08 (matched to chapter's grain).
2. **Edge vignette** — radial darkening 4% at corners, helps the image sit into atmosphere.
3. **Color grade tint** — `mix-blend-mode: multiply` with chapter's `palette.tint` color at 4% opacity.

Implementation:
```tsx
<EditorialImage
  src="..."
  alt="..."
  ratio="2:1"
  reveal="mask"
  grain      // default true
  vignette   // default true
  grade      // default true, uses chapter atmosphere palette
/>
```

Components composed under the hood:
```tsx
<div className="image-frame">
  <Image ... />
  <div className="image-grade" />     {/* color grade */}
  <div className="image-vignette" />  {/* radial darken */}
  <div className="image-grain" />     {/* grain overlay */}
</div>
```

---

## 6. Hover Treatment (desktop only)

- Default hover: subtle brightness shift (`filter: brightness(1.04)`) over 380ms.
- Optional: GLSL displacement on hover for case study key images (see `webgl-system.mdc`, displacement amplitude ≤ 0.04 UV).
- Magnetic image lift (`transform: translateY(-4px)`) for clickable case study covers.

### Constraints
- Hover effects on **clickable images only**. Decorative images do not respond to hover.
- No "Ken Burns" continuous zoom on hover.
- No image swap (image A → image B) on hover.

---

## 7. Image-as-Image, Not as Carousel

- **Carousels are forbidden** as a default presentation pattern.
- Multiple images in a sequence must be presented as either:
  - A **horizontal pinned case study** (see `scroll-system.mdc`).
  - A **vertical editorial sequence** (each image its own scene with reveal).
  - A **deliberate gallery grid** (max 4 images per viewport, asymmetric grid).

### Forbidden patterns
- ❌ Auto-advancing slideshows.
- ❌ Image rings / 3D rotators.
- ❌ Hover-flipping cards revealing alternate images.
- ❌ Image masonry walls (Pinterest-style).

---

## 8. Editorial Image Composition

### 8.1 Position rules
- Default editorial image position: **off-center**, weighted to a 3-column block in the desktop 12-column grid.
- Allow images to **bleed** to the viewport edge in one direction (left or right) for asymmetric tension.
- Always pair an image with **at least one beat of empty space** adjacent — minimum 80px breathing margin.

### 8.2 Pairing rules
- Image + caption: caption sits **below** image, sans-serif, `type.caption`, color text-muted, 24px below.
- Image + display title: title sits **above** image, never beside (vertical hierarchy reads as cinematic plate).
- Image + body copy: copy sits **opposite-column**, never wrapping the image.

### 8.3 Captions
- Captions are **always** present, even when "obvious".
- Format: `Photographer · Year · Place / Project`. Example: `Hiroshi Sugimoto · 2014 · Lake Superior`.
- Use **·** (interpunct) as separator (per `typography-system.mdc`).
- Captions reveal **after** the image, with a delay equal to `DUR.standard * 0.4`.

---

## 9. Video Treatment

If video is used:
- Always **muted by default**.
- Always autoplay only after `IntersectionObserver` confirms ≥ 50% in viewport.
- Always `playsInline` for mobile.
- Always `poster` attribute set with a blurred frame at LQIP quality.
- Maximum 1 video per chapter; maximum 4 per page.
- Source: AV1 (`.webm`) primary, H.264 (`.mp4`) fallback.
- Bitrate: ≤ 4 Mbps for hero videos, ≤ 1.5 Mbps for editorial inserts.
- Same atmosphere treatment as images (grain, vignette, grade overlays).

---

## 10. LQIP / Placeholder

- Use Next.js `placeholder="blur"` with custom `blurDataURL` for above-fold imagery.
- For below-fold, allow native lazy-load with no placeholder (atmosphere holds the visual until image arrives).
- LQIP color must match chapter atmosphere — never gray.

---

## 11. Implementation Standards

### Components
- `<EditorialImage>` — primary image primitive (`components/media/EditorialImage.tsx`).
- `<RevealImage>` — image with reveal direction prop.
- `<HeroImage>` — full-bleed hero with blur+scale reveal.
- `<CaseSlideImage>` — used inside horizontal case study slides, includes edge-drift reveal.
- `<EditorialVideo>` — video with same atmosphere treatment.

### Props
```ts
type EditorialImageProps = {
  src: string;
  alt: string;
  ratio: "2.39:1" | "2:1" | "3:2" | "4:3" | "1:1" | "3:4";
  reveal?: "mask" | "blur" | "drift" | "none";
  direction?: "left-to-right" | "right-to-left";
  caption?: { author: string; year?: string; place?: string };
  priority?: boolean;            // above-fold = true
  grain?: boolean;
  vignette?: boolean;
  grade?: boolean;
};
```

### Loading priority
- `priority` on the **single** above-fold hero image. Never on more than one image per chapter.
- Otherwise lazy via Next.js `<Image>` defaults.

### Storage
- All curated imagery in `public/images/<chapter>/`.
- Source masters in `assets/source/images/` (gitignored, synced via design ops).

---

## 12. DO / DON'T

### DO
- DO reveal every image with intention (`mask`, `blur`, or `drift`).
- DO grade every image with grain + vignette + chapter tint.
- DO crop deliberately, respecting subject and negative space.
- DO caption every image with author / year / place.
- DO use the Next.js `<Image>` component for all rasters.

### DON'T
- DON'T use carousels, slideshows, or auto-rotators.
- DON'T use stock photography.
- DON'T animate `top/left/width/height` on image entry.
- DON'T hover-swap images.
- DON'T over-grade — tints stay ≤ 4% opacity.
- DON'T crop circular avatars — this is not a SaaS team page.
- DON'T let images sit on plain background without atmosphere treatment.

---

## 13. Cinematic Rationale

- Every image in cinema is **lit, graded, and composed**. Every image on this site receives the same dignity.
- Mask reveals (left-to-right `clip-path`) read as **curtain-rises** — the most cinematic image entry available on the web.
- The 4% multiply tint is what makes images feel **of the chapter**, not foreign to it. Without it, photos look "linked", not "shot".
- Captions per image are not a UX nicety — they are **editorial credibility**. They turn a website into a publication.
